caption.text:
ğŸ‘€Looking for a ğŸvegetarian friendly dish that's EASY to make at ğŸ home? This Lo Mein is ğŸ˜TO DIE FOR. Get the recipe by Damn Delicious 
INGREDIENTS:

8 ounces lo mein egg noodles*
1 tablespoon olive oil
2 cloves garlic, minced
2 cups cremini mushrooms, sliced
1 red bell pepper, julienned
1 carrot, julienned
1/2 cup snow peas
3 cups baby spinach
FOR THE SAUCE
2 tablespoons reduced sodium soy sauce, or more, to taste
2 teaspoons sugar
1 teaspoon sesame oil
1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
1/2 teaspoon Sriracha, or more, to taste

DIRECTIONS:
In a small bowl, whisk together soy sauce, sugar, sesame oil, ginger and Sriracha; set aside.
In a large pot of boiling water, cook noodles according to package instructions; drain well.
Heat olive oil in a large skillet or wok over medium high heat. Add garlic, mushrooms, bell pepper and carrot. Cook, stirring frequently, until tender, about 3-4 minutes. Stir in snow peas and spinach until the spinach has wilted, about 2-3 minutes.
Stir in egg noodles and soy sauce mixture, and gently toss to combine. Serve immediately.

caption.text:
Fans of Right Gin may have noticed some changes to our packaging over the years. While the old bottle was beautiful, as bartenders began to incorporate Right into more and more exciting craft cocktails, they started to request a bottle that was easier to pick up, hold, use, and even store on the bar itself. â 
â 
When we received this feedback, we got to work selecting a bottle that would be beautiful, well-balanced for repetitive movements throughout a bartending shift, and ideal for creating delicious craft cocktails. We also wanted to be sure the diameter opening would fit the standard black pour spout snugly, to prevent leaking or slipping - a common oversight of many other bottles on the backbar and bar rail. At the end of the day, we realized that the right shape, size, and type of bottle was essential for RIGHT Gin, because â€œEst Unus Modus Verusâ€ - there IS a RIGHT Way. â 
â
